definition.value: A beta-diketone that is acetylacetone (acac) in which both methyl groups have been replaced by phenyl groups. It is a minor constituent of the root extract of licorice (Glycyrrhiza glabra) and exhibits antimutagenic and anticancer effects.
A beta-diketone that is dibenzoylmethane with hydroxy substituents at C-4 of one phenyl group and at C-2, -4 and -6 of the other.
An arginine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-arginine with the amino group of hydroxylamine.

A 13 amino acid peptide hormone which is found in the central nervous system and the gastrointestinal tract. It behaves as a neurotransmitter in the brain, as a hormone in the gut, and also as a neuromodulator. It is implicated in the pathophysiology of several CNS disorders (including schizophrenia, Parkinson's disease, drug abuse, pain, cancer, inflammation, eating disorders and central control of blood pressure) due to its association with a wide variety of neurotransmitter systems such as dopaminergic, sertonergic, glutamatergic, GABAergic, and cholinergic systems.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is isovitexin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a 6-(6-methoxycaffeoyl)glucosyl residue.
An organic chloride salt having iodonitrotetrazolium as the counterion.
An organic cation that is the cationic component of iodonitrotetrazolium violet.

An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-glucoside of 3-hydroxy-1H-indole in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively. It is used to test for the presence of an enzyme, beta-glucosidase, which cleaves the glycosidic bond to give 5-bromo-4-chloro-3-hydroxy-1H-indole, which immediately dimerises to give an intensely blue product.
An aromatic amine that is 1,2,4-triazole substituted at positions 3 and 5 by amino groups.
A hydroxamic acid obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of glycine with the amino group of hydroxylamine.
Any  fatty acid in which at least one of the aliphatic hydrogens is replaced by deuterium.
A disaccharide derivative that is isovitexin substituted at position 2'' on the glucose ring by a 6-O-sinapoyl-beta-D-glucosyl residue.
An EC 1.4.4.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-NH2 group, a disulfide as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of glycine decarboxylase (EC 1.4.4.2).
A tripeptide composed of glycine, L-histidine and L-lysine residues joined in sequence.

A 28-membered appetite-stimulating polypeptide consisting of Gly, Ser, Ser(octanoyl), Phe, Leu, Ser, Pro, Glu, His, Gln, Arg, Val, Gln, Gln, Arg, Lys, Glu, Ser, Lys, Lys, Pro, Pro, Ala, Lys, Leu, Gln, Pro and Arg residues joined in sequence. The O-n-octanoylation of the side-chain hydroxy group of serine-3 (Ser3) is essential for ghrelin's activity.
A disaccharide derivative that is isovitexin substituted at position 2'' on the glucose ring by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isoscoparin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by an alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucosyl moiety.
(E)-3,7,11,15-tetramethylhexadec-2-en-1-yl diphosphate(3-) in which both stereocentres have (R)-configuration.

A family of gastrointestinal peptide hormones that stimulate the secretion of gastric acid. Gastrin is found primarily in three forms: gastrin-34 ('big gastrin'), gastrin-17 ('little gastrin') and gastrin-14 ('minigastrin').

One of the primary forms of gastrin that is a 34-membered peptide consisting of Gln, Leu, Gly, Pro, Gln, Gly, Pro, Pro, His, Leu, Val, Ala, Asp, Pro, Ser, Lys, Lys, Gln, Gly, Pro, Trp, Leu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Ala, Tyr, Gly, Trp, Met, Asp and Phe residues joined in sequence.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isovitexin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by an alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucosyl moiety.
A C-glycosyl compound that is isovitexin in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 7 is replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
One of the primary forms of gastrin that is a 17-membered peptide consisting of Glp, Gly, Pro, Trp, Leu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Ala, Tyr, Gly, Trp, Met, Asp and Phe-NH2 residues joined in sequence.
An aryl phosphate resulting from the formal condensation of phosphoric acid with 1 mol eq. of 1-naphthol. It is a substrate for phosphatase.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where butyryl and oleoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and decanoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups, respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and lauroyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and myristoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and stearoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and arachidonoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A trimethoxyflavone that is flavone substituted by methoxy groups at positions 6, 8 and 4' and hydroxy groups at positions 5 and 7 respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where oleoyl and linoleoyl are the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
One of the primary forms of gastrin that is a 14-membered peptide consisting of Trp, Leu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Glu, Ala, Tyr, Gly, Trp, Met, Asp and Phe residues joined in sequence.
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is decanoyl (caprinoyl).
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is dodecanoyl (lauroyl).
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is tetradecanoyl (myristoyl).
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl).
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is octadecanoyl (stearoyl).
A 2-monoglyceride where linoleoyl forms the 2-acyl group.
A hydrazone that is hydrazonomalononitrile in which one of the hydrazine hydrogens is substituted by a p-trifluoromethoxyphenyl group.
An oligopeptide comprising five D-glutamic acid residues linked by peptidic bonds between the amino and gamma-carboxy groups.
The meso diastereoisomer of butane-2,3-diol.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is tricin substituted at positions 4 and 7 by beta-glucosyl 6-O-sinapoylglucosyl residues respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol where octanoyl and oleoyl form the 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has lauroyl and oleoyl as 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
An oligopeptide comprising nine D-glutamic acid residues linked by peptidic bonds between the amino and gamma-carboxy groups.
A  1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol that has myristoyl and oleoyl as 1- and 2-acyl groups respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol with palmitoyl as the 1-acyl group and oleoyl as the 2-acyl group.
